# [CCAMP](../wg/ccamp.html)

## Summary
The CCAMP working group met to discuss progress on several active data models and framework documents. Key topics included the refinement of optical pluggable modeling, the integration of AI-based Network Management Agents (NMA) into the ACTN framework, and emerging work on computation-aware traffic steering (CATS) and orchestration (UNACO) for optical networks. The session also covered updates to Fine-Grain Optical Transport Network (FGOTN) YANG models and path computation requirements, as well as cross-domain optical impairment sharing in WSON.

## Key Discussion Points

### WDM Pluggable Modelling
**Presenter:** Nigel Davis (on behalf of Reza Rokui)
**Slide Title:** [WDM pluggable modelling](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-ccamp-wdm-pluggable-modelling-00)
**Draft Reference:** [draft-ietf-ccamp-actn-wdm-pluggable-modelling](https://datatracker.ietf.org/id/draft-ietf-ccamp-actn-wdm-pluggable-modelling.html)

* Nigel Davis provided an update on the progress since IETF 124, noting that the document is now a working group draft.
* Work continues on a detailed Google Sheet to map pluggable attributes (capabilities, configuration, state, and performance management).
* The focus remains on line-side photonics, aiming to reuse existing IETF YANG models where possible and only developing new models to fill identified gaps.
* Future work will address the "backside" of the plug (host-to-plug bus) and multi-vendor interoperability challenges, including CMIS expansion.
* **Discussion:** Rod Van Meter inquired about access to the attribute tracking sheet. Nigel Davis clarified that the link in the slides should be globally readable and would be corrected.

### Integration of Network Management Agents into ACTN
**Presenter:** Xin Zhao
**Draft Reference:** [draft-ietf-ccamp-actn-optical-transport-mgmt](https://datatracker.ietf.org/id/draft-ietf-ccamp-actn-optical-transport-mgmt.html)

* Xin Zhao introduced a proposal to enhance the ACTN framework with AI-based Network Management Agents (NMA) to achieve higher levels of autonomy.
* The proposal introduces enhanced components for the CNC, MDSC, and PNC layers without replacing existing functional modules. It includes an "agent proxy" mechanism for multi-agent communication.
* **Discussion:** Daniele Ceccarelli suggested that while the framework is interesting, the work should focus on optical-specific parameters and ensure alignment with the NMO (Network Management Operations) group to avoid duplication of general AI agent frameworks. Haomian Zheng agreed, noting that the optical-specific use cases would be the primary landing spot for this work in CCAMP.

### Computation-Aware Traffic Steering (CATS) in OTN
**Presenter:** Meijia Wang
* The presentation explored how OTN technology can support CATS, specifically for high-performance workloads like AI training that require hard isolation and deterministic latency.
* The goal is to combine compute metrics (GPU load, memory) with optical layer metrics (wavelength, time slot availability).
* **Discussion:** Daniele Ceccarelli noted similarities between this and the Cross-Stratum Optimization (CSO) work from a decade ago. Haomian Zheng suggested performing a gap analysis against existing CATS metrics defined in the CATS working group.

### Unified Network and Computing Orchestration (UNACO)
**Presenter:** Zheng Han
* Zheng Han presented UNACO, focusing on joint orchestration between optical transport and AI computing infrastructure for distributed workloads.
* **Comparison with CATS:** Zheng Han clarified that CATS is focused on steering traffic over existing paths (ingress-triggered), whereas UNACO is a life-cycle orchestrator that provisions new optical circuits before traffic flows.
* **Discussion:** Haomian Zheng noted that while previous attempts at orchestration (like CSO) were started, the computation coordination part was never fully realized, and this work provides a necessary foundation for modern AI requirements. Daniele Ceccarelli commended the clear comparison between CATS and UNACO.

### FGOTN YANG Data Model
**Presenter:** Yanxia Fu
**Draft Reference:** [draft-ietf-ccamp-otn-tunnel-model](https://datatracker.ietf.org/id/draft-ietf-ccamp-otn-tunnel-model.html)

* Updates to the Fine-Grain OTN (FGOTN) models include a new `fg-otn-types` module and modifications to topology and tunnel models to support `FDUFlex`.
* The model now includes statements for FGOTN bandwidth under the max link and unreserved bandwidth attributes.
* **Discussion:** The authors requested working group adoption.

### PCE Requirements for Fine-Grain Transport
**Presenter:** Meijia Wang
* This draft outlines path computation requirements for FGOTN and FGMTN, driven by the massive increase in the number of fine-grained channels compared to traditional WDM.
* **Discussion:** Fatai Zhang noted that the term "FG Transport" is not an ITU-T standard term and recommended explicitly using FGOTN and FGMTN to avoid confusion. Oscar González de Dios suggested that if the requirements are strictly for PCEP extensions, the document's home (CCAMP vs. PCE) should be coordinated with the PCE chairs.

### WSON Optical Impairment Information Sharing
**Presenter:** Kanshu
* The presentation addressed the challenge of sharing optical impairments (OSNR, GSNR, etc.) in multi-domain/multi-operator scenarios to facilitate fast restoration and SLA attribution.
* Constraints include limited observability at boundary nodes and the need to protect confidential physical layer information through abstraction.
* **Discussion:** There was some initial confusion regarding whether "domains" referred to multi-vendor or multi-operator scenarios. Kanshu clarified it involves multiple administrative domains (operators). Roberta Maglione noted this scenario is being discussed within the IOWN Global Forum regarding WDM peering between operators.

